Gutach: Even more safety for pedestrians
They are not 100 meters apart: On Tuesday in Gutach the new B 33 pedestrian light was put into operation at the village parking lot - within sight of the older town hall lamp.
Two plants so close to each other: intention or shield-bürgerstreich?
Gutach's mayor answered this question clearly yesterday.
"The town hall lamp was installed at the time because it secures the school path," Eckert explained yesterday.
The Kluser-Ampel secure both cyclists as well as bus passengers and the Bergle-inhabitants.
The plant officially put into operation yesterday was important for the Sulzbachweg/Kirchstraße intersection area.
We have the museum, two churches, spa park, the bus stop, a doctor and a bank as well as the traffic flow from the residential area ›Grub‹.
"With the high traffic and pedestrian volumes, another traffic light had to be provided for their safety," says Eckert.
This is also confirmed by Peter Arnold of the District Office of Offenburg.
"According to current measurements, around 12,000 vehicles pass through the municipality of Gutach on the B 33 every day, of which about ten percent are heavy-duty traffic," says Arnold.
Therefore, the construction of a further traffic light is more than necessary: "Security is simple here," says Arnold.
A total of four traffic shows had been carried out, a roundabout was also planned, but due to the narrowness in the crossing area Sulzbachweg/Kirchstraße again rejected.
According to Arnold, everything was tested before when the traffic lights were selected: "By means of a transporter loaded with particularly long logs, we have tested whether these vehicles can leave the Sulzbachweg on the B 33 without turning the traffic lights."
The traffic light system itself, which costs around 15 000 euros, is "the most modern thing that is currently available on the market," Arnold explained.
The system is equipped with coloured LEDs, which glow so strongly that the lights of the motorists can be easily recognized, for example, even in low sun.
And it is also economical: The older lighting systems consume about 100 watts, the new ones just eight watts.
There are three lighting systems per direction of travel.
Arnold explained the technology of the new system: It is equipped with two radar sensors.
If the pedestrian pushes the traffic light button, the upper radar sensor tests the traffic situation.
If the road is clear, comes immediately green for the pedestrian, if not, it takes about 15 seconds.
Another radar sensor checks whether the green phase for the pedestrian can be terminated.
"If a group or people with reduced mobility cross the street, the green phase will be extended, so everyone will safely cross the road," Arnold explained.
Of course, the driver has to think along as a partner and observe the road.
This was not the case yesterday: barely the traffic light showed green for pedestrians, an upper-class vehicle ran through - with bright red.
