A black box in the car?
US road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that can be found in the dashboard of each car.
The devices that record every kilometer driven and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the state planning offices to revise the outdated system for financing US roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and are in favour of the government using the small boxes to record the kilometres driven – and possibly where they were driven – and then using the information to calculate tax rulings.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The US Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of data protection concerns.
But while Congress cannot agree on a course of action, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently examining how they can switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
"It's nothing that we're just going to use," said Hasan Ikhrata, CEO of Southern California Assn. of Governments, who plans to record the miles driven by all California motorists in the state from 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for that is here.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is financed by the taxes paid by Americans at the pump, is bankrupt.
But America doesn't have as much gas as it used to be.
Cars use less gasoline.
The state mineral oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per litre) has not increased for 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax by one cent at high fuel prices.
"The fuel tax is simply not sustainable," says Lee Munnich, an expert in traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
"This is the most sensible option in the long term," he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is well received by urban liberals, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in such a way that congestion and climate-damaging exhaust gases are reduced.
The California planners rely on the system to develop strategies to achieve the state's ambitious, legally anchored climate change goals.
However, Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also delighted with the idea of having drivers pay for the journey.
"This is not a tax that disappears into a black hole," explains Adrian Moore, Vice-President of Reason's Directives.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, called on Congress to move towards mile-based billing.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the move, responding to the concerns of rural MPs who represent people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or to the city in everyday life.
Several states and major cities are nevertheless moving in this direction on their own.
Oregon, which is currently recruiting 5,000 drivers for the country's largest experiment, is the most committed.
These drivers will soon pay the miles instead of the mineral oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering such a thing.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the equipment, motorists were skeptical of the idea that the government could pursue any of their movements.
"Thoughts against Big Brother and such things were a big problem," explains Alauddin Khan, Head of Strategy and Outcome Management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test started, the Nevada ACLU warned on its website: "It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into adult surveillance devices."
There was no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to track the miles travelled, but not exactly when and where.
Thus, Khan said, the public would also be more reassured.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not start to help states tax motorists.
Rather, it was their goal to gain a foothold in an emerging market for motor insurance, where drivers are supposed to pay based on the miles driven.
However, the devices tested by her are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and provide only limited information, which are regularly uploaded by modem.
"People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded," said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
In some of these public pilot programmes, major mistakes have been made.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, the planners experiment with giving drivers a number of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they do not choose any equipment at all and instead pay a flat-rate fee based on the average miles driven by all residents of the state.
Others hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more functions than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a tax-paying device that can also pay parking fees, pay insurance only for miles driven, and collect speed data from other vehicles in real time, allowing drivers to avoid traffic jams.
"Car drivers are motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system," says a city planning document.
However, some traffic planners wonder whether all the talk about paying per mile is not just a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials stated that Congress could simply solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund by increasing fuel tax.
An additional one-off fee or annual charge could be imposed on drivers using hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little petrol, so that they too pay a fair share.
"There is no reason for an operation if an aspirin is sufficient," explains Randy Rentschler, Head of Legislation and Public Affairs of the Commission.
When we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and many other things.
