US border: "Super tunnel" discovered for drug smuggling
At the border between Mexico and the US, investigators have discovered and shut down a "super tunnel" for drug smuggling.
According to the US customs authorities, the more than 500 metre long tube between Tijuana and San Diego was equipped with electricity, railway tracks and a ventilation system.
Three suspects were arrested, eight tons of marijuana and almost 150 kilograms of cocaine seized.
According to the data, the tunnel had not yet been used.
"These cartels are stupid if they think they could dig under the radar," said the US attorney general of Southern California, Laura Duffy, at a press conference in front of a warehouse in San Diego, where one end of the tunnel had been discovered.
To the drug gangs, Duffy assured: "If you continue to build such tunnels and try to use them, we are determined to make this a huge waste of your dirty money."
Both the US authorities and the Mexican security forces are in a permanent fight against the drug cartels.
Since 2006, more than 77,000 people have been killed in Mexico in the context of drug crime.
Designed by experts
Due to the complex equipment of the tunnel, the investigators assume that it was designed by architects and engineers and that the construction took about a year.
The track system was equipped in such a way that electrically operated wagons could be used there.
On the Mexican side, access is in a building 80 meters from the border.
According to the authorities, a ladder leads 20 meters deep to the actual tunnel entrance.
The tunnel has a cross-section of 1.20 meters height and 90 centimeters width.
It would also have been appropriate to promote illegal immigration towards the United States.
Two of the suspects were arrested in connection with the cocaine fund.
The third, a Mexican, was arrested for the seized marijuana.
All three are threatened with a maximum sentence of life imprisonment, as officials said.
Eight such tunnels have been discovered since 2006, the press conference in San Diego continued.
However, it was the first time cocaine was found in such tunnel construction.
Usually cocaine is smuggled in smaller quantities and not through tunnels.
This shows the "desperation" of the drug gangs, whose traditional routes are now cut off, said Bill Sherman of the DEA drug investigation in San Diego.
They would do anything to get to the United States.
No details were given about the detainees, at least one of them was Mexican, they said.
You have to expect up to ten years of imprisonment.
