Esa decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Remote planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they want to launch in the coming years.
30 proposals were available, five are still in the race.
Far-off worlds.
Astronomers have already found more than 1000 planets in other stars.
No one knows whether there is life on at least some of them.
The choice is difficult: Should you look for gravitational waves?
Or rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or search for earthlike planets, perhaps discovering extraterrestrial life?
These are the questions that the European space agency Esa is in charge of.
For their "Cosmic Vision" programme, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that are intended to make research a decisive step forward.
The budget for such "L-Missions" is about one billion euros each.
The start is expected to be 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
30 ideas were on the table, five of them have now been shortlisted.
Numerous bodies examine the proposals, check with the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be made by the Scientific Programme Committee.
The Esa has selected a total of four major questions to which the missions of the "Cosmic Vision" programme, initiated in 2007, will find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes involved in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also the formation of planets orbiting these stars - are still in proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
In order to investigate this question, the space telescope "Cheops" will be launched in 2017, with which 500 already known planetary systems in our vicinity will be examined in more detail.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres and thus search for "biomarkers": gases that are considered an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is ultimately intended to shed light on the conditions that exist for the emergence of life.
The magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the particle radiation it emits with the planetary system play an important role.
These processes can be investigated exemplarily in our solar system.
With the "Solar Orbiter", the Esa has already approved an M-Class mission (where the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is scheduled to launch in 2017 and observe the sun's surface and activity closely.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to the researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet has played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, the Esa provides for the first of the three L-missions of the Cosmic Vision programme.
The probe "Juice" (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later it reaches Jupiter and is supposed to investigate the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons Europe, Kallisto and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
Space offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to investigate whether the laws of nature known to us are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could show physicists the way to a new theory under which all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter we are familiar with, which consists of stars, planets and living beings like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and galaxy clusters together, and dark energy, which accelerates the expansion of the universe.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of a second of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid", the Esa has already approved an M-Mission, which is scheduled to start in 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to investigate the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky, thus enabling conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could do the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will be left at the end of the selection procedure.
According to many experts, the best chances of obtaining an L-mission are "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
Physicists mean changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do that, the scientists hope behind the project.
The mission consists of a detector consisting of two or three probes, which is stationed in space.
In contrast to installations on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves that arose during the Big Bang, thus providing new insights into the emergence of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are still competing for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which is to explore black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", which is to detect and investigate earth-like planets.
Proposals for sample transport from Mars, the exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids as well as solar physics have already been eliminated.
