In his letter, Snowden offers the German authorities an offer of cooperation "when the difficulties surrounding the humanitarian situation have been resolved".
Frontier Airlines charges fees for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to 100 US dollars for passengers who wish to stow hand luggage on their flight.
Frontier Airlines intends to charge up to 100 US dollars for a piece of hand luggage and 2 dollars for coffee or lemonade, even if the announcement on Wednesday stated that passengers would be allowed to keep the entire can.
The new fee applies to hand luggage in the luggage compartment above the seat, small pockets below the seat are still free of charge.
Frontier stated that if the fee is paid in advance, you will be charged $25 and $100 for travelers who paid at the gate.
Frontier spokesperson Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee is aimed at moving travelers to take care of the payment in advance.
"We don't want to calculate this sum," she explained.
In 2008, airlines began to charge charges for the first and second checked baggage.
Passengers who tried to bypass them have therefore stuffed as much as possible into their hand luggage, which means that the luggage compartments above the seat are often overcrowded.
Fees are a way to get passengers to take less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee wasn't really about making money.
It was about the most loyal customers of Frontier, who had clearly expressed that it was becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who buy your tickets on the airline's website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger at the Frontier boarding gate may be allowed to take a piece of luggage free of charge, but the next person will have to pay $100 for a similar piece of luggage.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's website and check-in procedures were being changed so that passengers were informed of the fee before they came to the gate.
Frontier's new cabin baggage charge will only enter into force in the summer, with no exact date yet.
Passengers often complain about baggage surcharges and other charges, but airlines like to resort to them.
They argue that the transport of luggage costs money and passengers should pay for this service if they wanted it.
Many on Wall Street regard the new baggage charges as a sign that airlines are taking enough money to cover the costs of air travel after years of losses.
Most of them, however, have so far left their fingers on hand luggage charges.
Spirit Airlines Inc. was the first to charge for hand luggage three years ago and later Allegiant Air, also a low-cost airliner, followed.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
In a December 2011 report, he estimated that the Spirit hand luggage fee would raise $50 million annually.
Sorensen, who previously held a leadership position at Midwest Airlines, has recently flown with Spirit and was curious about what would await him at the gate if passengers were confronted with the company's unusual hand baggage charge.
"The boarding process was one of the smoothest I have experienced in my career in aviation," he said.
I expected to see teeth gnashing and tangible discussions at the gate.
"The plane was full," he said, "and the boarding went smoothly."
Frontier also follows Spirit for the 2 dollars required for coffee, tea, lemonade or juice.
The company explained that passengers who bought lemonade or juice could keep the whole can and refill coffee for free.
Water is still free.
US Airways had briefly tried to demand money for soft drinks in 2008, but reversed this seven months later after passengers complained and no other large company had moved in.
Frontiers Step to charge for hand luggage when passengers do not buy directly from the airline is the latest initiative to direct customers to their own website.
Airlines pay online travel agencies such as Orbitz 10 to 25 US dollars per ticket sold.
This gives all companies an incentive to move passengers to buy directly from them rather than via an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone furthest in this area.
In September, the company began to award only half as many frequent flyer miles when booking via an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, the miles were again reduced to 25 percent of the flight distance.
Therefore, a trip with Frontier over 1000 miles booked with a third-party provider brings customers only 250 miles.
Passengers can also reserve seats only for direct purchase on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base at its headquarters in Denver, but business is shrinking and the company is losing money.
Revenue decreased by 9 percent and flight capacity shrunk almost 13 percent in the first quarter, as reported in the financial report published on Wednesday by the parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic has tried to control Frontier's finances as part of the company's sale.
