Cocaine lawyer who warned drug boss against police investigation must go to prison
Basharat Ditta, 42, passed information to underworld size Neil Scarborough
The lawyer was afraid his secret drug addiction might come to light
He was sentenced to three years in prison by the Liverpool Crown Court
A well-known criminal defender who warned a drug baron of a major police investigation because he was afraid his secret drug addiction could be exposed was sentenced to three years in prison.
Basharat Ditta, 42, provided Neil Scarborough with sensitive information about his drug trafficking activities after being compromised by his own cocaine addiction.
The lawyer, nicknamed "Bash", was arrested in his home in 2011 after the police had monitored Scarborough, whom he had represented in a previous drug trial.
Officials watched Scarborough (32) deliver three bags of cocaine at the lawyer's house in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was with colleagues at a bar dinner.
The investigation revealed that Ditta regularly used Class A drugs after tests found traces of cocaine in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Over a period of eight months between January and August 2011, he attempted to obtain illegal information about the arrest of two men on behalf of Scarborough and one of his partners.
All four suspects were monitored by the police during a major investigation into heroin and cocaine trafficking in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
Together with 32 other people, they were later arrested after the police secured heroin and cocaine worth £1.5 million and £200,000 in cash during a series of house searches.
Ditta, 42, passed on information to the criminals because he feared his drug addiction could become public.
Today, Ditta, who works for the Forbes Solicitors law firm in Blackburn, was found guilty and convicted at the Liverpool Crown Court after a three-week trial on two counts for obstruction of justice.
He admitted cocaine possession in a previous interview.
The lawyer was convicted after the police found out in their investigation of Scarborough that he had been in regular contact with Ditta by telephone in February 2011.
Two investigators followed the suspect and saw him go to Ditta's house and put the drugs under the lawyer's garbage can with 60 percent purity in a black golf glove.
Shortly after delivering the drugs, Scarborough made regular calls to Ditta, who was at the Blackburn Rovers football stadium in Ewood Park for dinner.
The lawyer returned home, took the drugs, and then nine messages were exchanged between the two.
In court, it became known that Ditta was a "regular user" of cocaine after tests revealed Class A drugs in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested, but denied taking cocaine and said that he had spoken to the alleged dealer because he was his client and claimed that their discussion was subject to the 'lawyer's secret'.
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a number of credit cards, but they were secured and a hair sample was taken from him.
During the police interrogation, he stated that he was running an office under his private address as well as at the workplace, and clients would call him at home for legal matters.
In court, it became known that he had called on important actors in drug trafficking, some of whom he had previously represented, after significant arrests and informed them of what the investigators knew about them.
Attorney Anne Whyte said, "A criminal lawyer should know better than anyone else that you don't break the law."
Ditta is accused of abuse of his position as a criminal defender because he has been too involved with certain clients.
The relationship in question is not simply that of a drug dealer, but of a drug dealer who supplies his lawyer with drugs.
Some of his communications were undoubtedly legitimate, for he was the lawyer of these persons.
But that went far beyond the limits of a normal relationship between lawyer and client.
He countered the police investigation as much as possible so that they could continue to pursue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta brought his profession into disrepute.
He was too close to certain clients, especially Scarborough, and he allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta rejected any wrongdoing and claimed: "If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and wanted to pass on information to Scarborough, I would not wait 15 hours, but do so immediately."
But after the hearing, Superintendent Lee Halstead from the Lancashire police said: "Mr. Ditta took the step from a criminal defender to a criminal the moment he started acquiring drugs from organized criminals."
His cocaine addiction led to a hopeless compromise and made him receptive to the motives of leading members of organized crime who commissioned him to obtain valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must maintain the highest standards of integrity and ensure trust and confidence in the public.
Ditta has betrayed this trust and tried to entrenched himself behind the façade of his profession.
The Serious and Organised Crime Unit of Lancashire led the investigation against Ditta, which also led to a conviction in three cases of possession of cocaine and judicial disability, which underscores our determination to bring criminals to justice.
This case should be a warning to criminals and shows that no one can escape the arm of the law.
We'll find you and take you to court.
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years in prison after he declared guilty of the conspiracy to trade heroin, cocaine and cannabis.
Thirty-five other people involved in drug trafficking were sentenced to a total sentence of 153 years for drug offences.
On his website, Ditta published an area with questions and answers about himself in which he stated that his dream job was to represent clients on death row in America as a lawyer, that his ultimate guest at dinner was Mohammed Ali, and inequality of opportunity was the motivation for his work.
