What happens to my e-mail on the way?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
In the design of the Internet service, has e-mail been technically implemented in a similar way to traditional mail?
When designing early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, in the case of the basic technical protocols, attention has not been paid to establishing a stable foundation for a sound exchange of letters.
Therefore, a conventional e-mail corresponds to an open postcard rather than a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends an e-mail to "Benni", are the computers of the two connected directly?
The email program or the browser of Anna sends the mail to the mail server of their service provider in the first step.
For example, if she has a GMail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run via several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call his provider for the content.
Are conventional e-mails read along their way through the net?
Most mails are read several times by software robots on the go.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam mail, which is deleted immediately or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
For systems such as GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place context advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can display corresponding links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people also read the e-mails?
The probability of unauthorized persons reading an e-mail is extremely low.
Theoretically, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement authorities and secret services also have legal opportunities to intercept or take note of e-mails.
In addition, there are possible illegal spying actions.
Is it possible to protect e-mails against readout?
With encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be effectively encrypted against readout.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to mask the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not possible to easily recognize who communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google on the email market in Germany?
According to a study by Convios Consulting from August 2013, Yahoo and Google play only a minor role in the mainly privately used mailboxes.
