The fire department managed to get a puppy to safety, which was stuck on a 15 - meter - high ledge in a rock face.
The nine-month-old Cockerspaniel female Ruby had run away after a traffic accident on Sunday afternoon and survived three days alone before she was rescued from a quarry on Wednesday.
Scott Alderson, 25, and his friend Becky Hall, 20, who owns the dog, came to the Flappit quarry in Denholme, West Yorkshire to welcome Ruby back and thank the firefighters of the West Yorkshire Fire and Rescue Service.
They had desperately searched for their missing bitch and published calls for help on social networks when she escaped to the quarry after the small traffic accident.
Around 2:15 p.m. on Wednesday, a walker who carried out his dog saw the stranded Ruby on the 15 meter high heel in the quarry.
The technical rescue team of the Cleckheaton Fire Station hurried to the spot and drove off to rescue Ruby, who was then transported up in a dog box.
Andy Clayton, a technical rescue team specialist, said: “She was in a dangerous situation.
It was located in the middle of the rock wall – 15 meters from the top and the ground.
She didn't move a muscle during her rescue – she was frozen.
But now she's fine.
She ate some dog pies afterwards.
That was quite an unusual assignment.
The fact that the dog was discovered is incredible.
Peter Lau, a specialist in the technical rescue team, said: "Ruby was very lucky."
There was the possibility that she was very badly injured or worse.
Ruby was taken to the vet for examination, but found nothing other than exhaustion and dehydration.
Becky Hall from Halifax, West Yorkshire, said: "Watching the rescue was scary."
I couldn't believe she was really up there.
It was wonderful to hold her in her arms again.
The veterinarian explained that if the exhaustion had become too big and it had collapsed, it would probably have crashed.
The firemen did a great job.
It was really brave what they did.
We are just so grateful and each one of them was absolutely incredible.
