George Kerevan: European Unbundling Gives Scots the Choice
A new day, a new horror story about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership.
This is the key word for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed wire border along the Hadrian Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde presentation highlighted the possible economic benefits that would bring more freedom of travel in the rest of Europe, but this did not play a role in the headlines, as expected.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules if it is more favourable to them.
As Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continuing non-observance for Brussels would only be a small concession in return for what you really want from the Scots.
So not really a story.
And one that has come so long that it already resembles a fossil: the first time I heard the "Independence means passport controls" duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient story.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance according to the European whistle?
Why exchange the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great post-war plan for the unification of Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the project Europe has officially died.
Across the EU, parties that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic party Alternative für Deutschland – founded only this year – won nearly five million votes in the Bundestag elections in September, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic resistance to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
The current economic crisis, however, turns out to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in connection with the straitjacket in which the respective national economy is forced to adhere to the single currency, many people believe that the European project has gone too far.
The crisis of the euro has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has pegged its members to exchange rates that are beneficial for German exporters – and German politicians would like to leave that.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the local currency, Southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – spurred by Berlin.
Behind the current budgetary and monetary problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the "green" energy directives imposed by Brussels – a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the world's wage fixings do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is coming up, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France's political elite saw the EU as a vehicle with which to keep Germany in check and to lift Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimation and has pushed on Europe's own economic policy, with which the troubled French economy has to fight.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, anti-EU Front National has just won a decisive by-election, placing the ruling socialists in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split in the right-wing spectrum would automatically bring benefits to the left.
What is Le Pen doing with her newly gained popularity among the white French of the working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties perform well in these elections – and this is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become something more like the 'Europe of the (sovereign) nations' which General de Gaulle favoured.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may stick to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of being flattered by the United States.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be alone in Atlantic rain.
Where's Scotland with all this?
We can decide to be a region of (finally) small England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can put themselves where.
I suspect that Scotland could go quite well in a looser European network if we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similar countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider equalising Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour finance minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition were responsible for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to be forced into austerity by Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Grow Up Faster
Afro-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white agemates, as studies show.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe that epidemic obesity is a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned when her daughter grows breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics in Orlando, Florida this week, paediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and were a new norm.
"I spend a lot of time calming parents down – normally this is no sign that puberty is coming up quickly," Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic hair, armpit hair, and body odor, are seen in girls earlier.
Nevertheless, there has been only a slight shift in the age of the menarchs (appearance of the first period) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
"When the development of breasts begins, it takes at least two to three years to reach the Menarche," said Kaplowitz, author of the book "Early puberty in girls: The essential guide to dealing with this frequently occurring problem."
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually marks the beginning of puberty, but it is 'touching' if breast enlargement is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight years.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can monitor closely.
If progress is faster, tests by an endicronologist may be indicated so that serious problems such as tumours or cysts can be excluded.
There are treatment methods to delay an early menstruation and to defend against another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the rate of development, the growth rate and the emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about drugs, but he admits: "The suppression of puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and the feelings of girls to be different from their agemates."
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have the period.
"They are worried about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side," said Kaplowitz.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter got her days when she was ten.
Even though there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home scared and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other food, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media are causative.
Boys come to puberty like girls used to.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported the conduct of a study in 2001 on girls aged six to nine years, which establishes a link between body fat and entry into puberty.
Other studies support this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, Afro-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white agemates.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to the climate to genes.
Another puzzle: Although boys have already grown facial and pubic hair earlier, the trend towards full-scale previous puberty is not as pronounced as with girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is widespread even in babies and toddlers.
"We need to be careful how to identify the true beginning of puberty," said Dr Lawrence Silverman, a paediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This can mean that you have to have a conversation sooner than expected," advised Kaplowitz.
If you stay calm, the child usually reacts well.
Girls who bloom early need the insurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than expected.
Jumbo manufacturers argue over seat width in the face of large orders
There has been a dispute between leading aircraft manufacturers over the width of tourist-class seats on long-haul flights, which sets the tone for a bitter clash on the Dubai Airshow this month.
The dispute revolves around the seat width that passengers are offered on long flights in the tourist class – not always those that airlines are the most striving for, but this designated space is the key to the efficiency claims on the latest Airbus SAS and Boeing Co. aircraft.
This week Airbus called for an industry standard that requires a seat width of at least 46 cm (18 inches) in the tourist class, but the US arch rival Boeing says that airlines should decide.
The confrontation comes at a time when the aircraft builders are competing to sell even larger versions of their two-engine long-haul aircraft and expect record orders at the event from 17 to 21 November.
How the rear part of the aircraft is designed – in particular whether there are rows with nine or ten seats – is crucial for the stated economic results that the new "mini-jumbo" design is intended to deliver.
Boeing claims that its modernized 777X has 406 seats in the tourist class, which are over 17 inches wide and thus allow ten per row.
Airbus explains that the competing version of the A350 transports 350 people in 18-inch seats in the tourist class, with nine per row.
Aircraft giants often distribute blows through technical details by means of advertising in the trade press.
Now Airbus is appealing directly to the public in front of the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to make the race with over 100 orders.
Recently, the company presented an ad that could be the beginning of a new ad war, showing donors a picture in which three people sit squeezed together in a restaurant, with the title: "Would you accept that?"
"Boeing proposes long-haul flights in seats that are tighter than regional turbo-props," says Airbus sales manager John Leahy.
People are getting fatter in the face of changing eating habits, but airplane seats have not changed radically.
Between the early 1970s, when the Boeing 747 defined the modern long-distance journey, and the end of the century, the weight of the average male American between 40 and 49 years increased by ten percent, according to data from the U.S. Department of Health.
According to US health statistics, the waist circumference of the male average American in the 21st century is 100.8 cm.
Airbus says its rival adheres to a seating concept from the 1950s when the average body circumference of the newly baptized Jet Set was narrower.
According to Airbus, studies have been carried out to show that one additional inch (2.54 cm) per seat increases sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing contests Airbus' figures on seat dimensions and says that it is not at the discretion of manufacturers to decide how airlines will strike the balance between air fares and equipment.
The company also explains that according to investigations, the experience in the aircraft depends on more than the seat width.
"It really means giving airlines flexibility to do what they think they need to do to be successful," explains Boeing cabin expert Kent Craver.
They don't want us to dictate to them what makes them profitable.
They know their business better than anyone.
For passengers, it is about more elbow-free, but for manufacturers, it is becoming increasingly an issue that can affect sales.
Behind the debate is a race for aircraft orders with an estimated volume of at least 700 billion US dollars after list prices in the coming decades, which could have a lasting impact on the export balance of the US or Europe.
As Reuters first reported in July, the seat layout is the driving force behind the battle over the new jets.
Both Airbus and Boeing maintain 20 percent more efficiency per seat in their latest two-engine long-haul designs than the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 77-300ER.
Boeing's statements on the results depend in part on comparing the 777X with its ten seats per row with the original design of nine seats in the 777.
The increase in unit costs is still lower than for machines currently in use with ten seats per series.
"Boeing therefore squeezes more seats into its aircraft in order to make it more competitive with our products," says Kevin Keniston, Head of Passenger Comfort at the European Airbus.
On the other hand, analysts say that full cabins with ten seats per row with existing 777s indicated that many passengers chose the tighter arrangement, which could be accompanied by cheaper air fares.
"Eightteen inch seat width would be great for passengers, but the reality is: from an economic point of view, the Airbus offer is controlled by the 777 threat," says Mary Kirby, cabin equipment expert, founder and editor of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not offer seats, but a catalogue of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
The world-traveling jet sellers even carry band measures to measure the setup in the competition.
Even if they price the comfort, all manufacturers also offer jets with highly compressed design for low-cost airlines and regional flights.
Airbus offers an A350 with ten-seat rows, but has not sold one, according to its own statement.
Until recently, Airbus has stressed the importance of increasing the adaptability of the cabins and offering wide seats on the aisles for some jets.
Without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern jets, experts say that the call for a new industry standard is likely to thwart, but could distract from the wave of 777X sales.
New anti-nicotine vaccine could help the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
Further trials are needed before human tests, which may take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal from Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results were good.
"We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can once help millions of smokers who have tried to stop trying all the methods available on the market, but have experienced that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches," Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information for the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies chase the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, causing a smoker to experience no nicotine high.
In trials, vaccinated mice administered nicotine maintained their normal level of activity.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, had taken a "time-out", the researchers explained, a sign that nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Vaccinations had to be given so frequently to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
However, the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower, as it transforms liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, if a future vaccine for humans is safe, it could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely that smokers would use it to stop.
"They then know that when they start smoking again, they no longer feel pleasure in it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that helps them to quit the habit," he explains.
British scientists said the results were interesting, but at the same time warned that further research was needed.
