Rules on electronic equipment in aircraft remain in force in Australia for the time being
Australian air passengers must continue to switch off tablets and smartphones at take-off and landing, despite efforts in the US to loosen regulations for such devices.
The US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) allows US airlines to change their requirements so that passengers can read, watch or play e-books on their devices during critical flight phases, provided they are in "flight mode".
During most of the flight, passengers are already allowed to do so, but many people find it annoying that they are not allowed to read their e-books at take-off and landing.
However, Australian companies are not following the decision that US airlines have to do a lot of work to implement it, but are not pursuing any immediate plans to change their rules.
CASA also stated that the announcement would be looked at, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic equipment in critical phases of flight in Australia still apply.
"CASA currently has no specific rules on the use of electronic equipment in aircraft," was announced.
The issue is subject to provisions requiring airlines to maintain safety at all times and passengers to comply with the safety instructions provided by cabin crew.
Virgin has already had talks with CASA about extending the use of his Wi-Fi entertainment system on flights and has declared that changes are open to change, but these must be initiated by the legislator.
"We would welcome a review of CASA's approval of electronic devices, because we are convinced that this would improve the customer experience after we now offer (wireless entertainment) during the flight," said one speaker.
Qantas said that, until further notice, we will stick to the current rules.
"Our current guidelines stipulate that electronic devices should not be used during take-off and landing, and we currently have no plans to change that," the company said.
The FAA rules apply to US airlines.
However, we are always interested in developments in regulations from which passengers can benefit, and we will certainly look closely at the FAA decision and the reasons behind it.
The decision has different effects for US companies depending on the age of the fleet.
They must demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate radio interference from mobile devices, and change manuals, training materials, hand luggage programs, and customer instruction.
"After confirming the tolerance of their fleet, an airline can allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at any height," the FAA announced.
In rare cases with poor visibility, the crew will instruct the passengers to turn off the equipment during landing.
The group also recommended stowing heavier equipment safely under the seat or in the compartments above the seats during take-off and landing.
