Pawnshops are booming in Singapore as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
In a pawnshop at the Bendemeer shopping centre in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a golden bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay her daughters' school fees.
"My husband and I have just bought a house, and all my money is in it," says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (about 1,730 euros) each month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not sufficient, she explains.
Indeed, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is so high that ValueMax, where it has made its exchange, has become the third pawnshop to be listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Pawning jewellery is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore require an annual percentage rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4 percent required by the United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same shopping centre.
Pawnshops, however, offer the advantage that no verification of creditworthiness or proof of income is required here, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region are turning to pawnshops after families feel the pressure from rising living costs as well as increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to loose fiscal policies in developed economies, families with lower and middle income are looking for pawn shops to compensate for the difference in stuttering economies.
This week, the rating agency called Standard & Poor's growing fiscal debt, mainly through rising mortgages, a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
According to the Agency, Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest budgetary debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also worried about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which this week has just come out of a technical recession.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing weakness in exports and a decline in consumer demand.
"In the end, this means that in view of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible," says Song Seng Wun, economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical highs in gold prices over the past two years have reinforced the trend to pledge personal items, as people take the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the 200 pawnshops of the city state are gold.
People say to themselves, "The price of gold looks good, let's pledge grandmother's gold chain and get it back next month."
The largest Thai pawnshop operator, EasyMoney, has seen 20 percent customer growth in its stores in recent months.
The growth in the deposit business is so strong that ValueMax, the operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighbouring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company is financing this with 60 percent of the 66 million Singapore dollars it received this week with the IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders were caught in the crossfire due to high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnshops not only offered cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also did not directly increase the debt.
"Customers borrow items they already own and the liquefaction of personal valuables does not increase household education," she explains.
The pawn lending business is increasingly accepted as short-term, hedged financing.
Also, not all people who use pawnshops are in financial difficulties.
Rich people from Singapore also come to the stores of ValueMax to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
We have customers from every social class.
"These include wealthy people who borrow for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses who need to bridge cash flow bottlenecks," says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
