Rescue package over 325 million Australian dollars for Tasmanian healthcare
The Australian government insists on the harsh conditions associated with the bailout package of over 325 million Australian dollars for Tasmanian healthcare to ensure that the state government cannot waste the money.
Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek has announced that the Commonwealth will take "immediate measures" to avert a crisis caused by an aging population of the island state, a higher rate of chronic diseases and system restrictions.
The funding for a period of four years was decided after government consultations with the independent Tasmanian deputy Andrew Wilkie.
"The government has put together an emergency rescue package that we believe addresses the unique challenges facing the state," said Plibersek today.
The $325 million package includes $31 million in emergency aid for electoral services.
A further 2600 operations, including orthopaedic surgery and cataract treatments, are intended to eliminate residues.
In addition, there is money for day clinics in Hobart and Launceston, better aftercare after inpatient stays, specialist training, mental health services and the introduction of a system for electronic recording of health data in local hospitals.
"These investments are in line with the ideas I received from hospital staff that they are the best way to improve the Tasmanian health system," said Tanya Plibersek.
The minister insisted on strict reporting and accountability by the Tasmanian government.
The state had to maintain the current level of funding in order to receive money from the Commonwealth and report on a monthly basis on where the additional funds were spent.
A three-member Commission will be set up to ensure that the state provides health services as effectively and efficiently as possible.
As Wilkie said today, the $325 million would be of little use if "they were not accompanied by real reforms that will put the Tasmanian public health system on a more sustainable path."
Nevertheless, he praised the government for responding to his request for urgent assistance, which he had first expressed to the Prime Minister at the beginning of May.
"I am confident that federal aid will make a major contribution to removing the state's public health system from the care list," said Wilkie.
According to the state government, these electoral achievements will largely offset recent cuts.
But the opposition spokesman for health policy at federal level, Peter Dutton, believes that today's announcement is only a "pattern solution".
"We are in today's situation because the Labor State Government has withdrawn 430 million dollars from the healthcare system," he told ABC TV.
It can't be that a state government rips almost half a billion dollars out of the system and the Commonwealth puts 300 million in it and then pretends to be the good news.
Dutton urged Plibersek to guarantee that not a single dollar of the bailout would be spent on additional bureaucracy.
