Syria has destroyed its ability to produce chemical weapons, according to a monitoring group
Syria has destroyed important facilities for the production of chemical weapons and jet gas ammunition, the global Chemical Weapons Monitoring Group declared on Thursday, while severe clashes occurred in the north of the country near one of the sites where toxic substances are suspected to be stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people had been killed since the beginning of the civil war three years ago.
The announcement of the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) was made one day before the date on
1 November, which the Hague-based organization set up in Damascus to destroy or make 'inoperable' all facilities for the manufacture of chemical weapons, including all machines for mixing chemicals into poison gas and filling ammunition.
The completion of this process, which is basically the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at the destruction of all Syria's chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
Damascus, however, still has to begin to destroy the existing weapons and supplies.
It is estimated that there are about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and the nerve gas sarin.
The announcement came at a time when fighting took place on Thursday in the city of Safira, where experts say there is a chemical weapons production facility and storage facilities, as reported by the UK-based Syrian Human Rights Observatory.
The activist group, which is tracking the number of deaths through a network of activists in Syria, stated on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 were civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the side of the government, 29,954 of them belonged to the army of President Bashar Assad, 18,678 were pro-government fighters and 187 Lebanese Hezbollah militias.
Also among the dead were 2,202 deserted army soldiers and 5,375 fighters of the opposition, many of them foreigners.
On 25 July, the UN estimated the number of deaths in this conflict since March 2011 at 100,000.
This number has not been updated yet.
The conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country.
Assad's troops have been fighting in Safira for weeks against the rebels, many of whom have ties to al-Qaeda groups.
The Observatory said that there had been losses on both sides on Thursday, but did not give details.
The fighting underscores the danger posed by chemical weapons inspectors, because their mission to free Syria from its poisonous arsenal is a race against time in the midst of a raging civil war.
According to the OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, the team is "now convinced that it has seen and witnessed the destruction of all the important production and mixing/filling facilities mentioned by Syria."
Therefore, "no further inspection activities are currently planned."
At the beginning of the week, the inspectors had declared that they had completed the first round of inspections and had visited 21 of the 23 sites indicated by Damascus.
The inspectors said that it was not possible to visit two facilities because of safety concerns.
On Thursday, the OPWC stated that the two sites had been "discontinued ... and the objects of the chemical weapons program that were there had been transferred to other facilities mentioned, which were inspected."
It was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities that the OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has presented a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which must be approved by the OPWC Executive Committee next month.
"I take a hat against the bravery and courage you have all shown in fulfilling the most challenging mission ever carried out by this organization," said Ahmed Uzumcu, Director General of the Monitoring Organization, in a comment published by OPCW.
For three years now, the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels have been fighting in this civil war against Assad's government and its security forces, which include many members of the Alawites, a secession of Shia Islam.
In view of further developments, the head of the observation group, Rami Abdurrahman, said there had been a strong explosion on Wednesday in an air defense facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia.
The cause of the explosion is unknown, he explained.
Anger over Judgment for Bali Bombers
Survivors and relatives of the 202 people killed in the Bali bombing in 2002 were angry at the verdict for the last of the instigators to be brought to justice, because they believed Umar Patek was to be legally shot.
Patek, who was on the run for nearly ten years as one of the most wanted persons in Southeast Asia, was sentenced to 20 years in prison yesterday for his role in the construction of explosive devices for the bombing.
If he was suspended, he could be released after 15 years.
The 45-year-old was found guilty of mass murder because of the attack on two nightclubs in the popular tourist area of Kuta, where 202 people died, including 88 Australians, and many others were injured.
A guilty verdict was also made on a number of terrorist charges, including a wave of explosive attacks on churches in Indonesia on Christmas Eve in 2000.
The prosecution had demanded a life sentence, even if it could have applied for the death penalty for the man, who is also called "Demulation Man" because of his reputation as a master bomb maker.
The decision has aroused painful memories with June Corteen, a mother from Perth who lost her 39-year-old twin daughter Jane and Jenny in the devastation caused by Patek and his co-conspirators almost ten years ago.
Fighting with tears, she said Patek should have been sentenced to death.
I really mean, he should follow in the footsteps of the other guys.
"You should put him in front of a firing squad," Corteen told AAP.
I have to live every day with the fact that I will not have any more grandchildren and I will never see my daughters again.
The Sari Club was razed to the ground when on October 12, 2002, shortly after 11 p.m., a huge bomb exploded in a small truck parked in front of the nightclub.
Peter Hughes was at Paddy's Bar, where a suicide bomber just 20 seconds earlier exploded a backpack filled with explosives.
He fell into a coma and died three times after the attack for a month while he was attached to a life support system.
Hughes said Patek deserved the same fate as the three other members of the terrorist cell Jemaah Islamiah – Amrozi, Mukhlas and Imam Samudra – who were responsible for the bloodbath and were executed four years ago.
Really, this guy should get the death penalty in front of everyone else.
To keep him alive – no, there is no reason to keep him alive.
Getting 20 years after killing 202 people and hurting many hundreds isn't much.
Patek is the last of the Bali bombers to stand trial.
He escaped arrest for almost a decade, but was eventually picked up in January 2011 in the Pakistani city of Abbottabad, where U.S. forces killed former al-Qaeda chief Osama bin Laden just four months later.
During the trial, an FBI agent testified that intelligence reports revealed that Patek was in Pakistan to meet bin Laden with the aim of reestablishing the link between Southeast Asian terrorist groups and al-Qaeda.
"He didn't turn himself in," Corteen said.
Until recently, he has shown no remorse for how much suffering he has inflicted on other people.
The verdict took place before the ten-year anniversary of the attack this year, which is celebrated with commemorations in Bali and Australia.
"There will be many tears this year," said Corteen.
Patek can still appeal against his verdict.
FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in aircraft (but do not have mobile phone calls)
Air passengers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies from take-off to landing, but not phone calls, according to the new guidelines issued on Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the USA.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
At a press conference, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained how quickly they would be implemented, depending on the airline.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the training manuals of the flight crew and the regulations for stowing the equipment in accordance with the new rules.
The FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic equipment in aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue were among these airlines.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA announced in a statement.
Passengers currently have to switch off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They may not take them off until the plane has reached a height of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing approach, passengers must turn them off again and must not take them off again before the plane has landed.
According to the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are protected against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the equipment also on take-off, landing and on the runway, the FAA explained.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been converted to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional association of professional flight attendants, welcomed the changes.
"If the new regime is implemented safely – and we work closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit from it," said Glading.
To be honest, we are sorry to have to feel like watchers on this issue.
Nevertheless, Internet connections to surf, exchange of e-mails, text messages or download of data under three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices in flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends", the Scrabble-like online game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011, when he had to leave an American Airlines jet publicly because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops still have to be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Cell phone calls during the flight are also prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not with the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices at take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker from the National Transportation Safety Board, a national traffic safety expert on CBS News, said that mobile phones were still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause disruption to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also interfere with transmission masts," says Rosenker.
A industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure on the FAA has increased to loosen restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri argue that there are no valid security grounds for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly more difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies mention that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the shutdown of the device.
In 1966, the FAA began to restrict the use of electronic devices by air passengers after reports of disruptions to navigation and communication equipment caused by passenger-guided FM radios, which were the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA so that they do not mind electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering Wi-Fi to passengers for several years when the altitude is reached.
The pilots adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for greater use of electronic equipment under the new guidelines, said Huerta.
Today's electronic devices generally emit much less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, emit minimal radiation when flipping.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
One of the advocates of easing restrictions on the use of equipment by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-reader and made a test flight to investigate problems, but could not detect any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using equipment.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he felt that the interference with the equipment was genuine, even if the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee said that there were only isolated reports from pilots who spoke in favour of a malfunction of aircraft systems by the equipment, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order the shutdown of the equipment by passengers in case of instrument landing under poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and called them a sensible adaptation for travelers who today would be extensively equipped with technology.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognises that a pleasant passenger experience does not conflict with safety," said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
