Is Europe’s elite ready to do business with Britain?
Business for Britain was launched in April with the intention of bringing the economy together and defining what those who care for prosperity and work in the UK want to change in our relations with the EU.
To this end, we have commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey among British business leaders and asked them what they think about Britain, the economy and the EU.
YouGov surveyed over 1,000 business leaders, roughly representing the UK's size, sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will surprise many.
We have found that the vast majority of companies are now exporting outside Europe and are focusing on countries that are modernising and growing while countries in the EU are stagnating.
They hope that new trade links with countries such as China, India and Brazil will be favored by the government rather than the long and strenuous process of reforming the obscure EU institutions.
In their view, on certain issues regulated by law – from antitrust law to product legislation – the majority of business leaders believe that control of these key competences should be restored to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the internal market, as companies claim that the cost of Brussels rules would now outweigh the benefits of being part of Europe’s trading zone – even 40 percent of large companies agreed with the traditionally most Europe-friendly.
Finally, and this probably says the most, our survey of business leaders showed that a clear majority of Britain wants a course to change the agreement and a relationship with the EU based on trade, not politics.
This insight, which is found among companies of all sizes and leading corporations, shows that the economy is pushing for a "sensible change" that brings the volume of action back to Britain.
It is a lot – a change in the agreement and better conditions for Britain would lead to a change of opinion in favour of staying in the EU in a referendum at 16 percent.
The Prime Minister should have no doubt: this survey shows that the British economy is behind his plan to renegotiate the British conditions for EU membership.
It also shows that companies expect a significant shift in power relations back to Britain from a renegotiation.
A better deal for the British economy is possible and increasingly necessary after the eurozone is now moving towards closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in the UK, as the result of our survey shows, which means greater attention to trade and a fundamental change in the Brussels approach to regulation for businesses.
Alexei Miller of Gazprom calls pipeline in Bulgaria the beginning of a new gas era
