Hearing before the Royal Commission: Two YMCA employees accused of sexual offences against Jonathan Lord
Two YMCA employees from New South Wales (NSW) had been charged with sexual offences related to children before charges were brought against the child caretaker Jonathan Lord from Caringbah in 2011, as the Royal Commission on Sexual Abuse of Children learned.
However, in the opening statement to the Commission, the YMCA stated that "in the organisation, there had never been an incident of sexual child abuse".
Managing Director Phillip Hare was questioned about a case in which a YMCA employee had been charged with offences involving child pornography, and another in which a sports instructor at YMCA Caringbah Hall had been convicted of abuse of children entrusted to him in 1991.
Hare told Gail Furness, one of the Commission's assistant lawyers, that he had known about the first case, but had not known the second.
He admitted that the opening statement from YMCA to the Commission was also inaccurate in the claim that "there had been external reviews of YMCA which recognised YMCA as the front line in child safety".
On the contrary, evidence before the Commission shows that the YMCA was informed that it received the second lowest rating of four possible in a quality audit conducted by the Department of Education and Communities in August of that year.
Hare, who started at the YMCA at the age of 21, admitted that the management had failed to hire Lord "from me down" and did not ensure that employees were aware of their obligations to report violations of child safety guidelines.
Lord had been convicted at the beginning of the year of sexual offenses against twelve boys during his two-year employment for the YMCA.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
