Scientists were able to shed more light on the connection between a dog’s tail wiggling and his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs waved more to the right with their tails (from the dog's point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and react to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "In humans it is well known that the left and right brains react differently to stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions."
Here we have tried to look at this with other species.
He also noticed that in dogs, just like in humans, the right brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the emotions.
In order to learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tail-wielding of their peers, the researchers monitored the animals while watching these films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the quadrupeds and analyzed the behavior.
We will probably soon understand why the cock moves in one direction, in the other direction
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed the dogs films with dogs – either a true-to-life version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right."
When the animals saw an otherwise expressionless dog moving the tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the waving dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tilt was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog, who is waving), her heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience, in which movements they should be worried about and when not.
He said: "If you have different encounters with other dogs, and if you are connected with the tail in one direction rather with friendly behavior and the right side produces a less friendly behavior, then you react on the basis of these experiences."
The researchers say that the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
John Bradshaw, an expert in dog behavior and visiting fellow at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine at the University of Bristol, stated that this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right were important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found out that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it's a satisfied dog.
Another research project at the University of Victoria in Canada said: "Dogs tend to approach a robot dog when its 'tail' turns left and not right instead of getting restless – exactly the other way around than in the Italian study."
According to his statement, the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs in the various studies.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
"Although there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brain halves are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception," says Bradshaw.
However, since their behavior is easy to record, it will probably not take long for us to understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other direction.
