Pope Francis appoints first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will be appointed new Cardinals of the Catholic Church for the first time on 22 February, as the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest-ranking clerics in the Catholic Church after the Pope and they are also the ones who elect a Pope, so that Francis will appoint the first group of men who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached the age of 80 is no longer able to take part in the election of the Pope – this is the case of a group of 120 "electoral cardinals".
In a statement in which the news was announced, Father Federico Lombardi, a spokesman for the Vatican, said that a meeting of all Cardinals would take place before the ceremony for the appointment of the new Cardinals, also known as the Consistory, was held.
"Pope Francis has decided to announce his decision to convene the Consistory in February in advance so that other meetings that require the participation of cardinals from all over the world can be planned," Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said that the number of elective cardinals would probably have dropped by February.
He said that a pope normally appoints as many cardinals as he needs, so that the number of elective cardinals would be 120 again, and as many cardinals as 80 as he wants.
The Consistory next year was important because it was the first since the election of Francis in March of this year, Valero said.
At present there is a certain overhang on the part of Europe and Italy in particular.
"It will be interesting to see if the new Pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance," he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they only have a tiny number of cardinals.
The Cardinals will also be the first to be called since the formation of the Council of Cardinals founded by Francis, a group of eight Cardinals from all over the world who have the task of finding ways to reform the Church.
In the past, the Pope decided everything alone.
"Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him," Valero said.
He said that it was "possible" for Francis to ask the Cardinals for advice.
