An Obama dialer's cry of despair
I have twice elected President Obama in the hope that change is possible
He says Obama has made commendable efforts that have been thwarted by Republican blockade tactics
The blockade policy does not excuse the website problems of Obamacare, the drone attacks
Obama's memoirs on the 2008 election campaign were a sad reminder of what would have been possible
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second year student at Harvard Medical School.
I'm reading a terribly sad book right now.
It is a book that I believed would cheer me up during the gloomy second year of my medical studies and give me hope again.
It is called "The Audacity to Win" and describes Barack Obama's memoirs for the 2008 presidential election.
When I finish my patient records at night and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and took a breath away from a speech.
The election became a landslide victory and news spokesmen stopped to show the historical significance of this hour.
My classmates wept with joy and my parents gathered all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
At that time, when Obama took office in 2008, he had 82% approvals.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is an evil awakening, as if you are being ripped out of a dream.
It is difficult to remember these optimistic times – they seem to be a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I voted for the first time, something has actually changed.
But it's just nothing I could have imagined.
I acknowledge the great and versatile things that Obama has achieved, from the adoption of the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the forced concealment of homosexuality in the army and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I, too, believe that the party-political blockade tactics have overturned too many efforts to push our nation forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name but a few.
But after defending the Obama administration countless times against colleagues and acquaintances, I have come to the end of my attempts to explain.
I have reached a point of political despair.
The republican blockade policy cannot explain why foreign heads of state are allowed to interrogate or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on Americans' private lives and why whistleblowers are punished that expose state misconduct.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why the public funding and spending limits were circumvented during the presidential elections.
It does not justify the results of a report which states that the White House's efforts to restrain the media are 'the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration'.
And most recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the adoption of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at the age of 18 that government work could have contradicted its previous political campaigns.
Obviously, the Congress is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and coincidental events such as the Newtown massacre shape the public debate.
But when I look at the above examples, they seem to be largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012, not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was a confusing and unextriced alternative, he seemed unable to define his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfil the hope we had heard of for so long.
But with Obama’s support falling to less than 45% this week, the book’s return to 2008 has become all the harder.
It awakens in me the longing for the many promises that have dissolved into air.
This week I read a section in the book that describes how Obama had to take a serious loss against Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
In a meeting with the election workers after the decision, he told his employees that they had to get back on track and follow the purpose of their cause.
"I want us to find our magic again," he said.
We need to remember who we are.
It's five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn't agree more with you.
The views expressed in this comment are exclusively those of Nathaniel Morris.
