On the way through mud, rivers and jungles for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical assistance to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
In the West African country there are not many doctors, only one for 5,000 people
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the Top 10 to vote him "CNN Hero of the Year".
The winner receives $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, Cameroon's capital city, in 1981.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then there was an inflammation that spread to his brain and caused a hematoma that would affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," says Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five o'clock in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
On the other hand, in the United States, a doctor has a ratio of 413 persons.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most Cameroonians would not be able to afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three quarters of health expenditure in the country is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty," says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his fellow countrymen suffer made Bwelle mature the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team performed 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped almost 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday he and up to 30 people squeeze themselves in minibuses and drive with the tied medical equipment on the roof over unpaved terrain to the villages that need help.
Things don't always go smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will be welcomed like heroes: a feast, song and dance, and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and Bwelle – with his broad smile and unlimited energy – likes to attend the happy celebration.
The next morning, the team will start examining hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per journey," says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometres around the village – and on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates – a document required for school, but many poor families simply cannot afford it.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The surgery usually takes place in a school, town hall or apartment; after the surgery the patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next.
The lighting for the surgery and the disinfection equipment is fed by the generator of the group and thus Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early morning hours on Sunday.
It's an exhausting amount, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
"They drum all night so that we can stay awake and continue our work," says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team goes back to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mixture of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – performed 700 free surgeries last year and knows that their work makes an enormous difference for the people she helps.
A man explained that the free operation of a hernia that he had received now enabled him to work again.
"This changes the future of my family," the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's sleeping," says Katie O'Malley, who is studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia for the second year and volunteering for Bwelle's group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe and support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gain practical experience that they would never get at home.
"We can be in surgery where we can help drain blood or consider the instruments to be Dr. Bwelle," O'Malley explains.
That would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
The students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and bring frequently donated medical supplies.
Once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transport and instructions.
"He is undoubtedly a hero," says O'Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no limits.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life, fulfilling a promise he made to his Father, brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy to do this job," says Bwelle.
And I'm thinking about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to relieve the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website and find out how you can help.
