Tourism: descent to the Romans
At a length of about 120 metres, a sewage canal from the Roman period is preserved below Cologne.
If you visit Cologne, you will not pass the cathedral.
The two towers rise into the sky about 157 metres and make it the second highest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors, who marvel at the two filigree church towers, suspect that there is also a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in Cologne's underworld.
The meeting point for its guided tours is the service center of Cologne tourism directly at the cathedral.
The tour begins quite unspectacular: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the seventies, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore, of the remains of the old city walls, only that which was not too large remained.
Most users of the car park therefore rush past the Roman remains and leave only their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will find an archaeological site separated by metal bars in the parking deck D2.
About five meters high ruins of hand plate-sized stones can be seen.
"They are remnants of the Roman city walls, which were built in the second half of the first century AD," says Schulze.
Before it goes back to the daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper park level take a look into a dark, 15 meter deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which is unfortunately hardly noticed.
Next station of the tour is the Praetorium, and here the participants descend again into the depth.
Here we see the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the Praetor of the CCAA.
A visitor wants to know what CCAA means.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means "city of Roman law and city of the Agrippinens, founded under Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the emperor cult".
And the Praetorium is the former governor's palace, the power center of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the anteroom of the exhibition, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewer, which is preserved here at about 120 meters in length.
"You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you like," Schulze cheers up the guests.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After he has fetched the key at the cash register, he leads the group to a 16 meter deep, walk-in shaft.
"We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built its bath deep into the ground in order to get to the groundwater, which was indispensable for ritual washing.
To this day, at the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read through changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe becomes part of an archaeological zone on the town hall square, for which construction work is to begin shortly.
However, a few years will pass before completion.
